@jfduncan The problem is that you can't stop those roads being used whatever route option you prefer and it isn't clear (especially via Android Auto) what roads are being used on the overview.

@JCB_Digger @stevelitchfield Haha.

I see there's a few requests for better route planning regarding small and almost unusable roads (some even mentioning Devon and Cornwall) from some time ago, and little to no acknowledgement of the issue or plans to change, so I guess the Pro version may be a way off.
@JCB_Digger @stevelitchfield Maybe we need a Waze Pro.

@jfduncan The problem is that it plans routes based on the speed limit, not the actual speeds possible. Clearly country roads are usually NSL but very often aren't safe to use at a fraction of the limit. As such, it routes down inappropriate roads and you can't say 'please don't'.

@jfduncan Exactly what I thought, so presumably it just doesn't have enough data. I know TomTom did this years ago, as it was part of the offline advance route planning, plus data gathered from (ISTR) Vodafone users - meaning TomTom got data even from non satnav users.

@liamvictor @edwinhayward Mitchell and Webb nailed it. 

https://t.co/aAG1UDkFdU

@jfduncan I always thought it got average speeds on roads (including different times of day) based on actual driving data from users. So surely Waze knows nobody is doing 60mph, or anywhere even close? Maybe there aren't many Wazers down there (because it's so bad, there never will be).

@BradShort @stevelitchfield There really aren't enough options (seems more emphasis is put on customisation, crowd sourcing data etc) so you're not doing anything wrong. I've clearly used it with a distorted view of it based on living around lots of A and B roads, plus Motorways, so U roads didn't figure.

@stevelitchfield I know from my days going around with Navteq gathering map data that all the data exists to avoid any road based on a huge range of criteria, so I guess Google/Waze is simply not interested. Commercial systems cost waaaay more!

To clarify, these are not unpaved roads - but they may as well be.
You'd really not want to use them often. They can go for miles, and despite Waze seeing them as 60mph, you'd barely average 20 because of the hills and bends.

I love Waze, and I've used it almost exclusively for a few years now. But using it in north Devon, it loved directing us down narrow roads with few passing places - and there's no way to avoid C/U roads in the settings. Seems Google Maps is no better either. TomTom is far better.

@ChrisTheDJ I should add that some train companies did miscalculate and not hire enough drivers and relied too heavily on overtime, which needs to be addressed. But the same Government blaming drivers is also the same Government funding the contracts and forcing cost savings.

@KayWorboys @ChrisTheDJ It's how a lot of things are run, and you do need to find the right balance (perhaps not leaving EU and losing half your staff because they were told to go back to their country!). You can't ever have exactly the right level of staff when it takes longer to train than to leave.

@ChrisTheDJ The industry will always rely on some rest day work, as training a driver takes around 17 months, but one leaving can go in a few months. GB Rail won't pay for more drivers, and there aren't such things as agency drivers because it would be pointless. Better relations is key.

At this point a colleague called a PCSO who was on duty not too far away and came to assist, with her carer (who we had called) arriving shortly after. They helped her up and took her to hospital.

Otherwise she could have been there for hours, with only a full collapse being..

This was just as well because my phone rang again, to tell me the ambulance wouldn't be coming now. I was asked if I, or someone else, could take her to A&E, or alternatively call 111 and get advice. Perhaps a GP could attend instead, or a pharmacist.

She was still awake, but clearly not well. She managed to answer a few questions, very slowly and with difficulty, and we were able to call someone to let them know what was happening. They said they'd come straight away.

I was told to expect a wait of two hours, and told not to call back unless she deteriorated further. When you call 999 now, they ask if you're calling about a previous call. It feels like you're chasing an order for food, or phoning a vehicle breakdown service.

As a precaution, we called 999 and initially had to wait 5 minutes to be connected. Upon answering the usual triage questions, we were told that unless she went fully unconscious or was sick, it was a low priority due to shortages of ambulance crew.

I didn't realise just how bad things were with our NHS until yesterday, when a young girl came to our station and collapsed. She managed to say she wasn't feeling well and later admitted she'd taken/been given drugs. She was having difficulty breathing and had slurred speech.

...I still chose to wear a mask out. Clearly that didn't help me (because I don't wear one at home and it almost got me via school) but it hopefully helped others around me.

On the day we hear of a new variant, I suggest that we still wear masks for other people's protection.

..I usually get knocked for six with flu. At the rate I'm going, I should feel almost back to normal tomorrow (hopefully) and that's down to the vaccine. Ofc I'm still stuck indoors for another week. 

It's also worth nothing that I am hopeful I didn't pass it on to others as...

...I've been double vaccinated and am certain this is why I have had no breathing issues or temperature, although it hasn't been a nice experience (any more so than flu).

I am sure some will say this just means Covid is no big deal, but I disagree...

...my son had no symptoms besides a bit of a runny nose, but I felt like I had all the symptoms of flu - and a loss of smell and taste.

Surprisingly no mass headache or fever though (in fact, throughout I've had a normal temperature)...

The lateral flow tests were near instant, but the wife tested negative. We then spent the evening setting ourselves into quarantine and letting people know that needed to know. We also booked PCR tests and started the track and trace process.

Meanwhile...

If I've been a little quiet this week, it's because on Wednesday I got what I thought was the start of a nasty cold.

Then my son came home from school and said that two people in his class had tested positive, so we checked ourselves.
